d by the authorities, the general public, and the teaching and nursing staff. It demonstrates how wartime conditions changed special education, both during and after the war, and will appeal to social and medical historians, as well as those studying childhood, the voluntary sector and social policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren with disabilitiesxCarexHistoryy20th century. 0aChildren with disabilitiesxEducation. 0aChildren with disabilitiesxServices forzGreat Britain. 0aChildren with disabilities--Services for--Great Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzEngland. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xEvacuation of civilians. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh  a1921 Education Act.  aSecond World War.  adisabled children.  ahospital schools.  apostwar expansion.  aprewar developments.  aresidential special school.  aspecial day schools.  atraining colleges.  awartime experiences.1 aWheatcroft, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610335240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526103352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526103352/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles